## <ins>An Advance dive in datatypes</ins>

Now , lists and arrays are part of non primitive datatypes . List is used to collect items that usually consist of elements of multiple data types. An array is also a vital component that collects several items of the same data type.A tuple is a collection of objects which ordered and immutable. So these can be used to solve a series of problem .

---

### Question 1

> Convert Int to Roman Numerals

> Input :  
> 100  
> Output:  
> C

<ins>Answer:</ins>

```python
def intToRoman(num):

    # Storing roman values of digits from 0-9
    # when placed at different places
    m = ["", "M", "MM", "MMM"]
    c = ["", "C", "CC", "CCC", "CD", "D",
         "DC", "DCC", "DCCC", "CM "]
    x = ["", "X", "XX", "XXX", "XL", "L",
         "LX", "LXX", "LXXX", "XC"]
    i = ["", "I", "II", "III", "IV", "V",
         "VI", "VII", "VIII", "IX"]

    # Converting to roman
    thousands = m[num // 1000]
    hundreds = c[(num % 1000) // 100]
    tens = x[(num % 100) // 10]
    ones = i[num % 10]

    ans = (thousands + hundreds +
           tens + ones)

    return ans

# Driver code
if __name__ == "__main__":
    number = 3549
    print(intToRoman(number))

```

The <span style="font-size: 100%; display: inline-block;" class="MathJax_SVG" id="MathJax-Element-2-Frame"><svg xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="3.226ex" height="2.176ex" style="vertical-align: -0.338ex;" viewBox="0 -791.3 1389 936.9" role="img" focusable="false"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><path stroke-width="1" d="M109 429Q82 429 66 447T50 491Q50 562 103 614T235 666Q326 666 387 610T449 465Q449 422 429 383T381 315T301 241Q265 210 201 149L142 93L218 92Q375 92 385 97Q392 99 409 186V189H449V186Q448 183 436 95T421 3V0H50V19V31Q50 38 56 46T86 81Q115 113 136 137Q145 147 170 174T204 211T233 244T261 278T284 308T305 340T320 369T333 401T340 431T343 464Q343 527 309 573T212 619Q179 619 154 602T119 569T109 550Q109 549 114 549Q132 549 151 535T170 489Q170 464 154 447T109 429Z"></path><g transform="translate(500,0)"><path stroke-width="1" d="M234 637Q231 637 226 637Q201 637 196 638T191 649Q191 676 202 682Q204 683 299 683Q376 683 387 683T401 677Q612 181 616 168L670 381Q723 592 723 606Q723 633 659 637Q635 637 635 648Q635 650 637 660Q641 676 643 679T653 683Q656 683 684 682T767 680Q817 680 843 681T873 682Q888 682 888 672Q888 650 880 642Q878 637 858 637Q787 633 769 597L620 7Q618 0 599 0Q585 0 582 2Q579 5 453 305L326 604L261 344Q196 88 196 79Q201 46 268 46H278Q284 41 284 38T282 19Q278 6 272 0H259Q228 2 151 2Q123 2 100 2T63 2T46 1Q31 1 31 10Q31 14 34 26T39 40Q41 46 62 46Q130 49 150 85Q154 91 221 362L289 634Q287 635 234 637Z"></path></g></g></svg></span> subsequent lines describe each student over <span style="font-size: 100%; - The first line contains a student's name. <br>
- The second line contains their grade. </p>

Output Format  
Print the name(s) of any student(s) having the second lowest grade in. If there are multiple students, order their names alphabetically and print each one on a new line.

Sample Input

5  
Harry  
37.21  
Berry  
37.21  
Tina  
37.2  
Akriti  
41  
Harsh  
39

Sample Output  
Berry  
Harry

<ins>Answer:</ins>

```python
# Creating Lists
Name = []
Score = []
res_name = []

# Taking the name and score.
# Appending them into Name[] and Score[].
if __name__ == '__main__':
    for _ in range(int(input())):
        name = input()
        score = float(input())

        Name.append(name)
        Score.append(score)

# Decomposing set into list.
# Sorting the list.
temp = [*set(Score)]
temp.sort()

# Iterating through the Score[]
for i in range(len(Score)):
    # Comparing the value at index 1 of temp[]
    # with Score[], If true
    # append that index in Name[] into res_name[]
    if Score[i] == temp[1]:
        res_name.append(Name[i])

# Sorting them alphabetically.
res_name.sort()

# Fetching the names from res_name[]
for index in res_name:
    print(index)
```

### Question 3

> how we can sort a tuple (consisting of float elements) using its float elements.

```
Input : tuple = [('lucky', '18.265'), ('nikhil', '14.107'),
                  ('akash', '24.541'), ('anand', '4.256'), ('gaurav', '10.365')]
Output : [('akash', '24.541'), ('lucky', '18.265'),
          ('nikhil', '14.107'), ('gaurav', '10.365'), ('anand', '4.256')]

Input : tuple = [('234', '9.4'), ('543', '16.9'), ('756', '5.5'),
                  ('132', '4.2'), ('342', '7.3')]
Output : [('543', '16.9'), ('234', '9.4'), ('342', '7.3'),
          ('756', '5.5'), ('132', '4.2')]
```

---

<ins>Answer:</ins>

```python
def Sort(tup):
    # reverse = True (Sorts in Descending order)
    # key is set to sort using float elements
    # lambda has been used
    return(sorted(tup, key = lambda x: float(x[1]), reverse = True))

# Driver Code
tup = [('lucky', '18.265'), ('nikhil', '14.107'), ('akash', '24.541'),
    ('anand', '4.256'), ('gaurav', '10.365')]
print(Sort(tup))
```

### Question 4

> Programmers are lazy , and python makes them even more lazy , so can you write a one line code that reverses a list , get the first 5 elements and square them

```
def lazy_funtion(arr):
    #write your one line of code in after the return statement
    return
if __name__=='__main__':
    print(lazy_funtion([]))

```

<ins>Answer:</ins>

```python
def lazy_funtion(arr):
    #write your one line of code in after the return statement
    return list(map(lambda x : x*x ,arr[::-1][:5]))
if __name__=='__main__':
    print(lazy_funtion([3,5,3,2,6,9,2,3,5,2,4,5,2,3,3454,3453,321,7,4345,7]))

```
